Colt 1911 Model of U.S. Army, manufactured in 1918.
Serial No. 524562. Colt Serial no. range for 1918 is 233,601 to 580,600.
This gun was refurbished by Augusta Arsenal, exact date unknown but most likely during WWII. Gun was Parkerized, grips replaced and likely barrel replaced (barrel marked Colt .45 Auto, but no other marks). Gun is otherwise original. The "G" and non-serif "H" are the same on the frame and slide, both slide and frame are Colt manufacture and are consistently marked from the same manufacture date in 1918. This gun is 100% functional with no repairs or damage. Finish (Parkerization) is 98%. This is a fantastic arsenal rebuild of the classic 1911 by Colt.

I have the papers assigning ownership to my Father in 1961, from the arsenal. This gun has fired less than 100 rounds since the arsenal refurbishment.

Recently appraised at Peterson's Firearms in Albuquerque for up to $1000.00 retail.

Also includes the UTG carrying bag and a parts list and teardown instructions in the envelope.  I'll throw in the old parts incase you want them.  Whoever said these guns were not accurate never shot one.  This thing with very basic sights is on the money.  It goes bang every time too.  It had a bent firing pin and still went bang.  Didn't know it until I decided to rebuilt it.  I'm thinning out the collection and don't really need this one.  I hate to get rid of it though.  Email me for contact info.  I work nights and will get back to you as soon as possible.  I will try to be at the gun show Sunday with it as well so look for me walking around with the bag.  $450 is pretty firm, but open to trades. title: For Sale:  Heckler and Koch Benelli SpA armi
postcontent: HK and Benelli stamped M3 Convertible super 90 's which is a dual-mode both pump-action and semi-automatic shotgun , it is still in the box, I never shot it.The Benelli M3 is an updated version of the Benelli M1 shotgun. The M3 uses the same inertia recoil semi-automatic system as the earlier Benelli M1, but adds another Benelli-patented feature, which allows the shooter to lock the semi-automatic action and switch to the manually operated pump-action mode and back in the matter of seconds. The action type switch is located at the forward end of the forearm, and is formed as an annular knurled ring. Rotation of this ring either engages the action rods of the pump system and locks the semi-automatic recoil system, or disengages the action bars, locks the forearm and allows the inertia recoil system to operate the action automatically. This greatly improves the versatility of the shotgun, allowing it to fire low-powered ammunition (mostly of special purpose, such as less-lethal rubber or tear-gas projectiles) in the manually operated pump action mode, and to fire full power combat loads with slugs or buckshot in rapid semi-automatic mode. An underbarrel tubular magazine usually holds 7-8 rounds for police or military versions.

Gas block is the modernized squared config that adds to the durability and service life as well as provides FULL enclosure of front sight post. 

Just a thought from a Jarhead:

I love my ARs but when the SHTF I WANT an AK. 
If you ever have to use this in defense of your life, real world experience has taught me and the statistics back me up that range is not generally the deciding factor, neither is accuracy as you'll likely be bobbing and weaving as will the bad guy. Minute of man is just fine. It comes down to speed of deployment, reliability and the ability to defeat cover. The 7.62 x39 can engage past 300 yards but Ill call it a 300 yard round. That is more than generous in any likely scenario. What it does better than its contemporaries is destroy cover and run where few other systems can. Neither the 5.56 nor the 5.45 can hope to match the original AK's ability to deny the enemy cover and that's where the fight is won. Pick the right tool for the job. 




Valid ID required, By contacting me you assert you are not a felon.
